\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {1}{\ignorespaces HCCP at a glance. \textbf  {(a)} Heteroscedastic aggregator outputs $(\hat  {p}, \hat  {\sigma })$; nonconformity score $s(x,y) = |y - \hat  {p}(x)| / \hat  {\sigma }(x)$ scales the decision radius by local uncertainty. \textbf  {(b)} Mondrian calibration partitions the labeled data by $(y \times \hat  {\sigma }\text  {-bin})$; per-cell quantile thresholds $\hat  {q}_{k,b}$ restore class-conditional (T2) and bin-conditional (T3) coverage, while remaining compatible with \citet  {barber2020limits}'s pointwise impossibility. \textbf  {(c)} Three-axis OOD validation on TraitGym: trait-LOO reaches the finite-sample floor $0.002$--$0.004$; chrom-LOO and C$\to $M cross-dataset stay $\leq 0.077$.}}{2}{figure.1}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:concept}{{1}{2}{HCCP at a glance. \textbf {(a)} Heteroscedastic aggregator outputs $(\phat , \shat )$; nonconformity score $s(x,y) = |y - \phat (x)| / \shat (x)$ scales the decision radius by local uncertainty. \textbf {(b)} Mondrian calibration partitions the labeled data by $(y \times \shat \text {-bin})$; per-cell quantile thresholds $\qhat _{k,b}$ restore class-conditional (T2) and bin-conditional (T3) coverage, while remaining compatible with \citet {barber2020limits}'s pointwise impossibility. \textbf {(c)} Three-axis OOD validation on TraitGym: trait-LOO reaches the finite-sample floor $0.002$--$0.004$; chrom-LOO and C$\to $M cross-dataset stay $\leq 0.077$}{figure.1}{}}
